Possibly.

239
00:18:09,423 --> 00:18:13,760
- Should I drop down from the ceiling?
- Actually, sir...

240
00:18:13,844 --> 00:18:17,598
There's one thing I think
we can be fairly confident about,

241
00:18:17,681 --> 00:18:20,267
that is that they didn't
come up through the floor...

242
00:18:20,350 --> 00:18:22,436
I've got you, sir.

243
00:18:22,519 --> 00:18:25,230
That's all right.
Just come my way, Bough.

244
00:18:25,314 --> 00:18:28,942
- That'll bring me
right over the hole, sir.
- There's no need to panic.

245
00:18:32,154 --> 00:18:34,323
Can you see
the bottom yet, Bough?

246
00:18:34,406 --> 00:18:37,242
Not yet, sir. The shaft
appears to be narrowing.

247
00:18:37,326 --> 00:18:40,162
I'm just a little bit worried
I might get stuck.

248
00:18:40,245 --> 00:18:44,416
Trust me, Bough. You won't
get stuck if you just keep moving.

249
00:18:44,500 --> 00:18:47,169
Yes, sir.

250
00:18:47,252 --> 00:18:50,088
I'm okay, sir.

251
00:18:50,172 --> 00:18:52,549
Are you at the bottom
now, Bough?

252
00:18:52,633 --> 00:18:55,052
No, I am in fact
stuck now, sir.

253
00:18:55,135 --> 00:18:58,722
Oh, for God's sake, Bough.
Stay there! I'm coming down.

254
00:18:58,805 --> 00:19:01,934
Uh, I'm not especially sure
that's a good idea, sir.

255
00:19:02,017 --> 00:19:04,728
Don't worry.

256
00:19:04,811 --> 00:19:07,272
Be careful, sir!

257
00:19:10,484 --> 00:19:12,819
Gently does it.

258
00:19:12,903 --> 00:19:15,531
- Sir?

259
00:19:19,618 --> 00:19:22,454
- Are you all right, sir?
- Yes. I landed on something quite soft.

260
00:19:22,538 --> 00:19:25,207
- That was me, sir.
- Oh, good.

261
00:19:26,542 --> 00:19:28,544
What now?

262
00:19:28,627 --> 00:19:31,380
There's no way back
up there, that's for sure.

263
00:19:31,463 --> 00:19:33,465
But this must lead
somewhere.

264
00:19:33,549 --> 00:19:35,592
I'm slightly uncomfortable
in the dark, sir.

265
00:19:35,717 --> 00:19:37,845
There's nothing
to worry about, Bough.

266
00:19:37,928 --> 00:19:41,849
- It may be pitch black,
but we can still see.
- Can we, sir? How?

267
00:19:41,932 --> 00:19:44,601
The Bedouin monks of
the Al Maghreb mountains...

268
00:19:44,685 --> 00:19:47,020
developed a system
of sonic chanting.

269
00:19:47,104 --> 00:19:49,731
- I see, sir.
- The sound of their chanting...

270
00:19:49,815 --> 00:19:51,984
would bounce back
off any obstacles,

271
00:19:52,067 --> 00:19:54,236
and using their
highly tuned ears...

272
00:19:54,319 --> 00:19:57,072
they could paint a mental picture
of the path ahead.

273
00:19:57,155 --> 00:20:00,200
- Brilliant, sir.
- However, you must always
sing in E-flat.

274
00:20:02,786 --> 00:20:07,040
# E-flat, E-flat, E-flat #

275
00:20:07,124 --> 00:20:11,837
# Thank you for the music
The songs I'm singing #

276
00:20:11,920 --> 00:20:14,548
- Is it working, sir?
- Extremely well, thank you, Bough.

277
00:20:14,631 --> 00:20:16,550
# Thanks for all
the joy that... # 

278
00:20:16,633 --> 00:20:18,510
- 
- Ow!

279
00:20:18,635 --> 00:20:21,930
You all right, sir? I think
I can see something, sir.

280
00:20:22,014 --> 00:20:24,433
Oh, yeah. Come on.

281
00:20:42,701 --> 00:20:44,661
Here is the long one.

282
00:20:44,745 --> 00:20:46,788
It is a long one.

283
00:20:46,872 --> 00:20:48,832
Careful.

284
00:20:53,462 --> 00:20:55,672
- I knew it.
- Shall we call for backup, sir?

285
00:20:55,797 --> 00:20:59,593
What? And watch some fat-bottomed
bobby make our arrest for us?

286
00:20:59,718 --> 00:21:01,595
I don't think so.

287
00:21:03,722 --> 00:21:08,060
Good morning, gentlemen.
Ml7 at your service.

288
00:21:08,143 --> 00:21:12,898
Observe, Bough, the dull
incompetence of the criminal mind.

289
00:21:12,981 --> 00:21:17,069
It can never hope to match
our level of technical expertise.

290
00:22:02,865 --> 00:22:06,285
- You've got it.
- What do we do now, sir?

291
00:22:06,368 --> 00:22:08,370
Watch and learn, Bough.

292
00:22:12,374 --> 00:22:16,253
- They're too far ahead of us.
- Have faith, Bough.
They're heading south.

293
00:22:24,720 --> 00:22:27,431
- There they are, sir!
- Just as I thought.

294
00:22:30,809 --> 00:22:34,479
- Hang on tight, Bough.

295
00:22:41,028 --> 00:22:44,323
- We're never gonna catch them in this.

296
00:22:44,406 --> 00:22:47,284
- Take the wheel, Bough.
I'm getting in the Aston.
- Sir?

297
00:22:50,370 --> 00:22:54,082
Change places, Bough.
I'm getting out the other side.

298
00:22:54,166 --> 00:22:56,084
Sir?

299
00:23:15,896 --> 00:23:18,065
Set, Bough.
Take me up.

300
00:23:25,781 --> 00:23:28,367
Swing me out, Bough!

301
00:23:32,079 --> 00:23:35,457
- Whoa.
- Down.

302
00:23:39,920 --> 00:23:42,422
- Up! Up!

303
00:23:45,175 --> 00:23:48,053
Sorry!

304
00:23:50,180 --> 00:23:52,224
Bough, pull out!

305
00:23:57,437 --> 00:24:00,232
Ow! Ow!

306
00:24:00,315 --> 00:24:04,194
Those idiots
are right behind us. Faster!

307
00:24:26,758 --> 00:24:28,802
Uh-huh.

308
00:24:52,451 --> 00:24:55,037
Drop me here, Bough!

309
00:24:58,081 --> 00:25:01,460
Ow! Oh.

310
00:25:01,543 --> 00:25:04,755
No! No! No!

311
00:25:04,838 --> 00:25:07,174
Oh, no, no, no, no, no, no.

312
00:25:42,459 --> 00:25:45,379
They're turning into
the Brompton Cemetery.

313
00:25:45,462 --> 00:25:48,841
Get here as soon as you can.
I'm going in.

314
00:25:55,848 --> 00:26:00,143
In a wheelchair. But Geoffrey
overcame these terrible disabilities...

315
00:26:00,227 --> 00:26:03,939
with that simple resilience
and sunny optimism...

316
00:26:04,022 --> 00:26:07,109
that so warmed
all of us who knew him,

317
00:26:07,192 --> 00:26:09,528
spending the rest of his life
in the service...

318
00:26:09,611 --> 00:26:12,489
of the poor and disabled
of this parish.

319
00:26:12,573 --> 00:26:16,618
It's very good.
Really very good.

320
00:26:16,702 --> 00:26:19,329
No, no, please go on.
I'm sorry to interrupt.

321
00:26:19,413 --> 00:26:22,166
- It's very entertaining.
- Who's that?

322
00:26:22,249 --> 00:26:27,129
That priest act of yours should keep the
other prisoners entertained for hours.

323
00:26:27,212 --> 00:26:30,048
Oh, I'm so sorry. Where are
my manners? Johnny English,

324
00:26:30,132 --> 00:26:33,260
British Secret Service,
and you are all under arrest.

325
00:26:33,343 --> 00:26:35,888
I must say you've done
this whole thing very well.

326
00:26:35,971 --> 00:26:38,473
The attention to detail
is excellent.

327
00:26:38,599 --> 00:26:41,602
You, the grieving granny,
you're very convincing.

328
00:26:41,685 --> 00:26:45,647
Oh, look. Real tears.
Do you get paid extra for that?

329
00:26:45,731 --> 00:26:49,484
Ahh, what
we're all here for.

330
00:26:49,568 --> 00:26:52,988
I know! Why don't we
take a look inside?

331
00:26:53,071 --> 00:26:57,618
- 
- Oh, you've nailed it down!

332
00:26:57,701 --> 00:27:00,037
Why would you do that?

333
00:27:00,120 --> 00:27:04,917
I know you're gonna come back
in two weeks and dig it up again.

334
00:27:07,419 --> 00:27:12,299
Now, what are you playing in this
little vignette of deceit and villainy?

335
00:27:12,382 --> 00:27:14,426
I'm the hearse driver.

336
00:27:14,510 --> 00:27:17,179
- You're the hearse driver?
- Yes, sir.

337
00:27:19,431 --> 00:27:21,558
- You're the hearse driver?
- Yes, sir.

338
00:27:21,642 --> 00:27:24,520
Ah! Aha!

339
00:27:24,603 --> 00:27:27,940
There you are... Gunther.

340
00:27:28,023 --> 00:27:32,152
Uh, I do hope he hasn't
made a nuisance of himself.

341
00:27:32,402 --> 00:27:35,739
I'm Doctor, um...

342
00:27:38,116 --> 00:27:42,538
Bough, of the Lunatic
Response Unit.

343
00:27:42,621 --> 00:27:46,583
I'm afraid Gunther here wasn't
supposed to be released until 2028.

344
00:27:46,667 --> 00:27:49,378
Isn't that right, Gunther?

345
00:27:49,461 --> 00:27:53,757
Yes, yes, there's been
the most monumental cock-up.

346
00:27:54,508 --> 00:27:58,178
Um, if you'll excuse me,
with the deepest respect,

347
00:27:58,262 --> 00:28:00,472
utmost sympathy.

348
00:28:00,597 --> 00:28:03,183
Uh, he hasn't urinated
on anyone, has he?

349
00:28:03,267 --> 00:28:04,977
- No.
- No, no.

350
00:28:05,060 --> 00:28:09,231
That's a blessing. Are you
gonna give me the gun, Gunther?

351
00:28:14,736 --> 00:28:18,282
There. That wasn't
too difficult, was it?

352
00:28:18,365 --> 00:28:22,452
- Are you going to come home now?

353
00:28:27,040 --> 00:28:31,503
Oh... in the van!
Yes, we are going in the van.

354
00:28:31,587 --> 00:28:33,881
Yes, yes.
Vroom, vroom.

355
00:28:33,964 --> 00:28:37,050
- Vroom, vroom. Vroom, vroom.
- Yes. Yeah.

356
00:28:37,134 --> 00:28:41,513
- Yes. He's waving good-bye.
Good-bye, everyone.

357
00:28:41,597 --> 00:28:43,891
- Good-bye.
- Good-bye, Gunther.

358
00:28:43,974 --> 00:28:46,727
Mind the nice dead people.
There we go.

359
00:28:51,690 --> 00:28:55,694
Oh, we'll just go to the path
here. There. Big step.

360
00:28:55,777 --> 00:28:59,072
It's a graveyard. It's
where they bring people...

361
00:28:59,198 --> 00:29:01,241
Yes, all right.
You can stop now.

362
00:29:01,325 --> 00:29:05,078
- For appearances,
I'll just hold your arm.
- Just keep walking.

363
00:29:05,162 --> 00:29:07,539
In fact, run, run, run!

364
00:29:13,337 --> 00:29:17,007
I can't believe
I've done this.

365
00:29:17,090 --> 00:29:21,220
I mean, I really
cannot believe I've done this!

366
00:29:25,432 --> 00:29:28,644
You see, 200 years ago,

367
00:29:28,727 --> 00:29:33,565
my family should have inherited
the throne of England,

368
00:29:33,649 --> 00:29:36,401
but they were cast aside.

369
00:29:36,485 --> 00:29:39,738
Well, in a few
very short days,

370
00:29:39,822 --> 00:29:42,950
it will be back
where it belongs.

371
00:29:45,536 --> 00:29:48,080
With me.

372
00:29:48,163 --> 00:29:53,502
Shall I try it on?
Yes? No? Maybe?

373
00:29:53,585 --> 00:29:57,506
To make you king, we need
the archbishop of Canterbury to do that.

374
00:29:57,589 --> 00:29:59,633
The archbishop of Canterbury...

375
00:29:59,758 --> 00:30:03,637
is being taken care of
even as we speak.
TARGET ACQUIRED

376
00:30:03,679 --> 00:30:06,807
TARGET LOCKED

377
00:30:15,357 --> 00:30:19,111
There's only one thing, sir.
What are we going to do about English?

378
00:30:21,864 --> 00:30:25,784
If I were you, I wouldn't worry
too much about English.

379
00:30:25,868 --> 00:30:29,496
He is no threat to us.
I had his flat bugged.

380
00:30:55,772 --> 00:30:59,234
Clearly, the aptly named
English is a fool.

381
00:30:59,359 --> 00:31:02,863
He might be a fool, but he's
a fool who keeps showing up.

382
00:31:02,946 --> 00:31:06,867
Well, the next time
he shows up,

383
00:31:06,950 --> 00:31:08,994
eliminate him.

384
00:31:09,077 --> 00:31:10,037
Thank you.

385
00:31:11,455 --> 00:31:13,624
Dieter Klein
and Klaus Vendetta, sir.

386
00:31:13,707 --> 00:31:17,503
Released from prison six months ago.
327 convictions between them.

387
00:31:17,586 --> 00:31:19,630
Armed robbery,
grievous bodily harm...

388
00:31:19,713 --> 00:31:22,007
and combined parking fines
of more than 400...

389
00:31:22,090 --> 00:31:24,927
Uh, yes, all right. Thank you, Bough.
I think we get the picture.

390
00:31:25,177 --> 00:31:28,180
The point is, sir,
that Vendetta and Klein...

391
00:31:28,263 --> 00:31:31,642
are both in the employ
of Monsieur Sauvage.

392
00:31:31,725 --> 00:31:34,728
- Pascal Sauvage?
- Precisely, sir.

393
00:31:34,811 --> 00:31:37,564
But you're not suggesting
Sauvage is involved?

394
00:31:37,648 --> 00:31:39,733
I think he's more
than just involved, sir.

395
00:31:39,816 --> 00:31:42,194
I'm convinced he's
up to his French neck in it.

396
00:31:42,277 --> 00:31:45,656
Don't be absurd. Sauvage
employs thousands of people.

397
00:31:45,739 --> 00:31:48,867
Just because two of them
are villains doesn't mean that he is.

398
00:31:48,951 --> 00:31:51,912
I want him discounted from this
investigation immediately.

399
00:31:52,037 --> 00:31:53,914
Yes, sir.

400
00:31:57,167 --> 00:32:02,089
All right. Tonight I shall be
at Sauvage's reception
for the new French ambassador.

401
00:32:02,172 --> 00:32:04,842
Any developments,
you can reach me there.

402
00:32:04,925 --> 00:32:08,345
Apart from that, I don't want you
within a hundred miles of the man.

403
00:32:08,428 --> 00:32:10,389
Absolutely, sir.

404
00:32:10,764 --> 00:32:14,393
Requisition order: Ml7 quartermasters
for immediate supply;

405
00:32:14,476 --> 00:32:18,438
one military transport plane,
fully fueled, with permission
for nighttime city over flight;

406
00:32:18,480 --> 00:32:22,985
two night camouflage parachutes,
plus reserves, plus neoprene
bodysuits, twice, in black.

407
00:32:23,068 --> 00:32:25,237
I've never liked the navy blue.

408
00:32:25,320 --> 00:32:28,699
And a 40-inch chest for me
'cause I need the sleeve length.

409
00:32:28,782 --> 00:32:30,117
- Morning, Felch.
- Morning.

410
00:32:30,159 --> 00:32:32,578
Oh, and two Special Forces
signet rings,

411
00:32:32,661 --> 00:32:34,580
primed and colour-coded.

412
00:32:34,663 --> 00:32:37,207
- What's all this for?
- For tonight's operation.

413
00:32:37,291 --> 00:32:40,002
We're going to break into
Sauvage's headquarters.

414
00:32:40,085 --> 00:32:42,379
- But Pegasus said...
- Let me worry about Pegasus.

415
00:32:42,462 --> 00:32:46,675
I know that Sauvage
is behind all this, and tonight
we're going to get the evidence.

416
00:32:46,758 --> 00:32:50,053
- Is something wrong, sir?
- Did that sound like Felch to you?

417
00:33:18,081 --> 00:33:21,210
Bough...

418
00:33:34,973 --> 00:33:37,267
You, upstairs.

419
00:33:51,323 --> 00:33:53,242
Ow.

420
00:34:24,231 --> 00:34:26,275
Can you see him, Bough?

421
00:34:26,400 --> 00:34:29,486
He's on the upper level, sir.

422
00:34:34,867 --> 00:34:36,785
Got him.

423
00:34:42,749 --> 00:34:46,837
And like a coiled viper...
he strikes.

424
00:34:55,762 --> 00:34:58,849
So what you're saying, sir,
is there must have been two of them?

425
00:34:58,932 --> 00:35:01,143
Oh, at least, Bough.
Possibly four.

426
00:35:01,226 --> 00:35:03,270
I wonder why
I didn't see them.

427
00:35:03,353 --> 00:35:05,647
You mustn't dwell
on your mistakes.

428
00:35:05,731 --> 00:35:08,984
- You must learn from them, then move on.
- Yes, sir.

429
00:35:09,067 --> 00:35:12,946
- So where were you, sir?
- Just drop it, Bough!

430
00:35:16,867 --> 00:35:19,995
- Aah! What is it, sir?
- That bike.

431
00:35:22,247 --> 00:35:24,666
You get things
sorted out for tonight.

432
00:35:39,056 --> 00:35:41,850
Well, well, we meet again.

433
00:35:41,934 --> 00:35:44,436
Mr English.
What a pleasant surprise.

434
00:35:44,520 --> 00:35:46,563
I wondered when
you might show up again.

435
00:35:46,647 --> 00:35:51,068
On the contrary, Miss Campbell. It is
not I who keeps showing up. It's you.

436
00:35:51,151 --> 00:35:53,529
Do you like sushi?

437
00:35:53,612 --> 00:35:55,572
Hmm?

438
00:35:56,990 --> 00:36:00,494
Oh, sushi! I practically
live off the stuff.

439
00:36:00,577 --> 00:36:04,373
You might say the mysteries
of the Orient are no mystery to me.

440
00:36:12,923 --> 00:36:16,760
- Sake?
- Ah. Sake.

441
00:36:17,719 --> 00:36:19,721
Cheers.

442
00:36:19,805 --> 00:36:24,977
May all your daughters
be born with three bottoms.

443
00:36:32,067 --> 00:36:35,028
Now then, perhaps
you can explain how it is...

444
00:36:35,112 --> 00:36:37,656
that I run into you
at two crime scenes...

445
00:36:37,739 --> 00:36:41,326
and then can't find any record of you
on a single government computer.

446
00:36:41,410 --> 00:36:43,954
Shouldn't you ask
the government that?

447
00:36:44,037 --> 00:36:46,582
I am the government
and I'm asking you.

448
00:36:50,419 --> 00:36:52,212
Let me.

449
00:36:53,630 --> 00:36:56,133
Mmm. You're brave.

450
00:36:56,216 --> 00:36:59,261
They say that sea urchin's
the ultimate acquired taste.

451
00:36:59,344 --> 00:37:03,015
Hmm. It's a personal
favourite of mine.

452
00:37:07,352 --> 00:37:11,023
I think people are put off
by how it feeds through its bottom.

453
00:37:11,106 --> 00:37:13,317
Would you excuse me
for a moment?

454
00:37:32,252 --> 00:37:35,255
Excuse me. Sorry. I'm from Ml7.
Sorry. I'm a secret agent.

455
00:37:53,482 --> 00:37:56,401
- Everything set, Bough?
- Just about, sir.

456
00:37:56,485 --> 00:38:00,614
Actually, sir, do you mind if I
run through the plan one more time?

457
00:38:00,697 --> 00:38:02,950
- No, no.
- These are the two buildings here.

458
00:38:03,033 --> 00:38:07,454
This one is our target, Sauvage's
headquarters, next to City Hospital.

459
00:38:07,538 --> 00:38:10,749
I jump first and land
on the south side of the roof,

460
00:38:10,833 --> 00:38:13,961
abseil down 14 floors and
cut through this window here.

461
00:38:14,044 --> 00:38:17,881
I then land on the east side
and abseil down 12 floors.

462
00:38:17,965 --> 00:38:21,134
Where you wait for my signal
that I've disabled the alarm system.

463
00:38:21,218 --> 00:38:23,679
- Yes.
- You them break into this window here,

464
00:38:23,762 --> 00:38:26,431
work your way along the secure corridor
and penetrate Sauvage's office.

465
00:38:26,557 --> 00:38:29,518
- Yes, yes.
- Is that okay, sir?

466
00:38:29,560 --> 00:38:32,521
It's been okay ever since
I thought up the idea, Bough.

467
00:38:36,733 --> 00:38:39,653
Oh, I nearly forgot, sir.
Your laser beacon.

468
00:38:39,736 --> 00:38:42,656
- My what?
- Your laser beacon!

469
00:38:42,739 --> 00:38:45,325
It'll guide you
onto Sauvage's building.

470
00:38:45,409 --> 00:38:48,787
Your dependence on hardware
really does amuse me, Bough.

471
00:38:48,871 --> 00:38:51,582
I've been dropped
into the Kalahari Desert...

472
00:38:51,665 --> 00:38:56,003
carrying nothing more than a toothbrush
and a packet of sherbet lemons,

473
00:38:56,086 --> 00:39:00,257
and I still found my way
to Bulawayo before Ramadan.

474
00:39:00,340 --> 00:39:04,178
So thank you, Bough,
but no thank you.

475
00:39:07,014 --> 00:39:09,391
- Bough, go!

476
00:39:09,474 --> 00:39:11,935
Geronimo!

477
00:39:37,711 --> 00:39:42,257
- Fandango!

478
00:40:03,362 --> 00:40:07,741
Ugh! Ai-yi-yi.

479
00:40:12,579 --> 00:40:14,873
Right.

480
00:40:29,805 --> 00:40:33,225
- Alarm's disabled, sir.

481
00:40:33,308 --> 00:40:35,227
Roger that, Bough.

482
00:41:11,221 --> 00:41:14,099
This is worse
than I thought, Bough.

483
00:41:14,183 --> 00:41:18,228
Sauvage has got some kind
of laboratory set up here.

484
00:41:18,312 --> 00:41:21,356
God knows what kind
of sick operation he's running.

485
00:41:33,911 --> 00:41:36,622
My God, what
have they done to you?

486
00:41:36,705 --> 00:41:39,917
They've taken
some of my blood.

487
00:41:40,000 --> 00:41:43,378
- Bastards!
- It's only for tests.

488
00:41:43,462 --> 00:41:46,215
Of course it is.
Come on, my friend.

489
00:41:46,298 --> 00:41:49,384
Let's get you out of here
before they take anything else.

490
00:41:57,309 --> 00:42:01,355
Ah! Good evening,
Dr Frankenstein.

491
00:42:01,438 --> 00:42:03,440
This way, please.

492
00:42:03,524 --> 00:42:06,276
Come on.
I haven't got all night.

493
00:42:06,360 --> 00:42:09,238
And you,
you angels of death.

494
00:42:09,321 --> 00:42:11,990
About turn.
Come on, let's go.

495
00:42:12,074 --> 00:42:14,284
Come On, come On.
Keep moving.

496
00:42:14,368 --> 00:42:17,788
Come on. Over there. I know
what you're doing here. And you.

497
00:42:17,871 --> 00:42:20,916
Come on. Quicker. Quicker.
Over there.

498
00:42:22,334 --> 00:42:25,087
Now then,

499
00:42:25,170 --> 00:42:28,173
perhaps you could direct me
to your evil paymaster.

500
00:42:28,257 --> 00:42:32,636
- What are you talking about?
- You know exactly
what I'm talking about.

501
00:42:32,719 --> 00:42:36,598
Where is the office
of Pascal Sauvage?

502
00:43:00,497 --> 00:43:03,500
Are you coming over here
in a minute, sir?

503
00:43:05,752 --> 00:43:07,504
I'm from Ml7.

504
00:43:07,588 --> 00:43:10,424
This has been a test of your
emergency response systems,

505
00:43:10,507 --> 00:43:13,635
and I have to say
you've all done extremely well.

506
00:43:13,719 --> 00:43:16,805
Right.
Well, I'll leave you to it.

507
00:43:16,889 --> 00:43:18,891
And, uh, get well soon.

508
00:43:24,229 --> 00:43:28,317
Oh, God!

509
00:43:46,293 --> 00:43:48,545
Sir. Sir.

510
00:43:55,093 --> 00:43:58,388
Did you just land
on the wrong building?

511
00:43:58,472 --> 00:44:02,226
I did a precautionary sweep
of the immediate environment.

512
00:44:02,309 --> 00:44:04,311
Right.

513
00:44:05,479 --> 00:44:07,814
- And everything was fine.
- Good.

514
00:44:07,898 --> 00:44:10,025
Okay, let's go.

515
00:44:14,947 --> 00:44:19,535
I will be downstairs
at the reception...

516
00:44:26,083 --> 00:44:29,878
- That's far enough.
- Well, good evening.

517
00:44:29,962 --> 00:44:33,048
- Perhaps you'd like this as well.
- What is it?

518
00:44:33,131 --> 00:44:35,843
- Let me show you.
- Aah!

519
00:44:35,926 --> 00:44:38,387
Well executed, Bough,
but completely redundant.

520
00:44:38,470 --> 00:44:41,515
- How do you mean, sir?
- Super-strength muscle relaxant.

521
00:44:41,598 --> 00:44:44,935
When he wakes up, he'll be
as floppy as a damp old sock.

522
00:44:50,858 --> 00:44:52,651
What's this?

523
00:45:06,707 --> 00:45:10,169
That's the face of
the archbishop of Canterbury.

524
00:45:13,297 --> 00:45:16,008
What are they doing?

525
00:45:19,803 --> 00:45:23,098
What's this got to do
with the Crown Jewels?

526
00:45:44,119 --> 00:45:46,121
Bough.

527
00:46:03,096 --> 00:46:05,057
English.

528
00:46:05,140 --> 00:46:07,893
A people whose empire
once covered...

529
00:46:07,976 --> 00:46:11,271
one quarter of the surface
of the earth.

530
00:46:11,396 --> 00:46:13,649
Alas, no longer.

531
00:46:13,732 --> 00:46:16,902
My friends ask me, "Pascal,
how can you be so interested...

532
00:46:16,985 --> 00:46:21,073
in such a backward,
grotty little country?"

533
00:46:21,156 --> 00:46:23,867
My answer is simple:
The queen.

534
00:46:23,951 --> 00:46:27,746
The queen has more power
in her tiny white gloves...

535
00:46:27,830 --> 00:46:31,250
than any other head of state
in the entire world.

536
00:46:31,333 --> 00:46:33,627
She can declare war
or make peace,

537
00:46:33,710 --> 00:46:35,963
and most intriguingly...

538
00:46:36,046 --> 00:46:40,717
she can seize any piece of land
which takes her fancy.

539
00:46:40,801 --> 00:46:44,513
Of course,
the queen never uses...

540
00:46:44,638 --> 00:46:47,307
the enormous power
afforded to her.

541
00:46:47,391 --> 00:46:51,895
But imagine someone
who would use that power.

542
00:46:51,979 --> 00:46:55,482
Imagine, say, me.

543
00:46:55,566 --> 00:46:59,611
But how could he do that, sir?
How could he make himself king?

544
00:46:59,695 --> 00:47:01,780
The archbishop.

545
00:47:01,864 --> 00:47:04,283
- 
-

546
00:47:11,039 --> 00:47:13,041
Ow.

547
00:47:14,293 --> 00:47:17,754
Hands up.
There's a good fellow.

548
00:47:17,880 --> 00:47:19,631
Heavily armed for a late night
at the office.

549
00:47:19,715 --> 00:47:24,011
You fool, English. You'll never
get out of the building alive.

550
00:47:24,094 --> 00:47:26,305
I'd save your breath
for my questioning.

551
00:47:26,388 --> 00:47:28,265
I'm not telling you
anything.

552
00:47:28,348 --> 00:47:30,017
Incorrect.

553
00:47:31,268 --> 00:47:33,103
Sodium pentothal.

554
00:47:33,187 --> 00:47:36,565
- I won't lie to you. It's a truth serum.

555
00:47:36,648 --> 00:47:41,195
Now then, why does Sauvage
want to have himself crowned?

556
00:47:41,278 --> 00:47:44,448
You have no idea
what's going on here, do you?

557
00:47:44,531 --> 00:47:47,534
It would be funny
if it wasn't so "pablibblit."

558
00:47:47,618 --> 00:47:48,952
What?

559
00:47:55,542 --> 00:47:57,878
- He's talking gibberish, sir.
- I can hear that.

560
00:47:59,963 --> 00:48:02,841
- He's collapsed onto me, sir.
- I can see that.

561
00:48:02,925 --> 00:48:06,220
- You don't think you could've
got the syringes mixed up?
- What?

562
00:48:06,303 --> 00:48:09,139
Given the guard outside truth serum
and given Klein the muscle relaxant?

563
00:48:09,223 --> 00:48:11,141
Aah!

564
00:48:11,225 --> 00:48:15,521
Don't be ridiculous, Bough.
I think I know my right from my left.

565
00:48:15,604 --> 00:48:18,607
- Sir?
- Oh, bugger it.

566
00:48:20,150 --> 00:48:22,110
Bough, take "flodd."

567
00:48:22,194 --> 00:48:26,156
- Take what, sir?
- "Flodd." "Schlage."

568
00:48:26,240 --> 00:48:29,576
- I'm not quite getting
that second word, sir.
- "Schlaaaagh!"

569
00:48:29,660 --> 00:48:31,578
- Write it down, sir.
- "Schlaaaagh!"

570
00:48:31,662 --> 00:48:34,665
Yes!

571
00:48:35,958 --> 00:48:38,418
"C." C-A... Uh...

572
00:48:38,502 --> 00:48:42,256
Car! Take the car!
We came by plane.

573
00:48:42,339 --> 00:48:45,092
Bugger off!

574
00:48:45,175 --> 00:48:47,386
- Hold it right there.

575
00:48:47,469 --> 00:48:50,848
- What's wrong with them?
- I'm not telling you.

576
00:48:50,931 --> 00:48:53,725
Wrong answer.

577
00:48:53,809 --> 00:48:55,978
What is it with you two?

578
00:48:56,061 --> 00:48:58,272
Huh?

579
00:48:59,648 --> 00:49:01,316
Let's get outta here.

580
00:49:01,400 --> 00:49:03,277
Sorry, but who are you,
exactly?

581
00:49:03,360 --> 00:49:05,988
Special Agent Campbell.
I'm attached to Interpol in Paris.

582
00:49:06,071 --> 00:49:08,240
We've been watching Sauvage
for months.

583
00:49:08,323 --> 00:49:10,242
Why?

584
00:49:10,325 --> 00:49:13,412
Because every major convict released
from a Sauvage prison in six months...

585
00:49:13,495 --> 00:49:15,664
has been employed
by one of his companies.

586
00:49:15,747 --> 00:49:18,083
We believe he's recruiting them
for a major criminal conspiracy.

587
00:49:18,167 --> 00:49:20,752
- We just don't know what yet.
-

588
00:49:22,087 --> 00:49:24,298
- What did he say?
- Pegasus!

589
00:49:24,381 --> 00:49:26,675
We have to report
to Pegasus!

590
00:49:26,758 --> 00:49:28,677
Oh, no, sir.
No, no, no.

591
00:49:28,760 --> 00:49:31,763
- How do we get out of here?
- Hey, you two!

592
00:49:31,847 --> 00:49:34,516
What you did to me
really hurt.

593
00:49:34,600 --> 00:49:38,854
Yeah. Sorry about that. How do we
get out of here without being seen?

594
00:49:38,937 --> 00:49:41,607
Okay.

595
00:49:41,690 --> 00:49:45,402
Left by the fountain, right by the fire
exit, to the elevator at the end.

596
00:49:45,486 --> 00:49:47,821
- Thank you.
- Oh, my God.

597
00:49:47,905 --> 00:49:49,573
Nice job, Bough.

598
00:49:49,656 --> 00:49:52,451
- Left, sir. Left!

599
00:49:52,534 --> 00:49:55,496
Sir, you can't go
to Sauvage's reception in this state.

600
00:49:55,579 --> 00:49:58,373
The effect of the drug
has practically worn off.

601
00:49:58,457 --> 00:50:00,334
I'm "fline"...

602
00:50:00,417 --> 00:50:02,586
"schline"...
uh, "gline"...

603
00:50:12,304 --> 00:50:14,723
- Monsieur.
- Ah. Thank you.

604
00:50:18,685 --> 00:50:20,896
- Would you like another?
- Please.

605
00:50:27,027 --> 00:50:28,779
Thank you.

606
00:50:33,951 --> 00:50:35,994
What in God's name...

607
00:50:36,119 --> 00:50:38,038
Ah, Foreign "Sebretarary."

608
00:50:38,121 --> 00:50:40,582
Um...

609
00:50:40,666 --> 00:50:42,501
Aah!

610
00:50:42,584 --> 00:50:45,796
- Shall we dance?

611
00:51:33,719 --> 00:51:36,638
Excuse me, sir.
I'm very sorry to interrupt...

612
00:51:36,722 --> 00:51:38,765
Pascal, how nice
to see you again.

613
00:51:38,849 --> 00:51:41,393
- Enjoying the party?
- Oh, splendid affair.

614
00:51:41,476 --> 00:51:46,356
I was until I was informed
that your man English...

615
00:51:46,440 --> 00:51:49,276
and his curious boyfriend here
have spent the evening...

616
00:51:49,359 --> 00:51:52,779
breaking into my office
and assaulting my staff.

617
00:51:52,863 --> 00:51:55,991
- Is this true, Bough?
- Well, we... we...

618
00:52:06,001 --> 00:52:08,212
What do you think
you're up to?

619
00:52:08,295 --> 00:52:11,048
- Sir, if I could just offer...
- Go home, Bough!

620
00:52:11,131 --> 00:52:12,883
Now!

621
00:52:12,966 --> 00:52:15,511
I gave you direct orders
not to meddle with Sauvage.

622
00:52:15,594 --> 00:52:18,889
What do you do? Break into his office
and assault two of his staff.

623
00:52:18,972 --> 00:52:23,227
Then you march in here,
loaded with God knows what,
and insult the foreign secretary.

624
00:52:23,310 --> 00:52:26,021
I haven't encountered such
behaviour in Whitehall in 30 years.

625
00:52:26,104 --> 00:52:28,899
- But...
- There are no "buts," English.

626
00:52:28,982 --> 00:52:32,444
You're off the case. Your security
clearance is hereby cancelled.

627
00:52:32,528 --> 00:52:35,781
After a three-month leave of absence,
you will return at your old grade.

628
00:52:35,864 --> 00:52:38,867
And I hope never
to hear your name again.

629
00:53:29,501 --> 00:53:31,795
English has seen too much.

630
00:53:31,879 --> 00:53:34,298
We go to plan "B."

631
00:53:34,381 --> 00:53:36,675
Get rid of
the fake archbishop...

632
00:53:36,800 --> 00:53:39,595
and green-light
the visit to Her Majesty.

633
00:53:39,678 --> 00:53:43,348
Then this pathetic country
can humiliate itself...

634
00:53:43,432 --> 00:53:45,976
by crowning me officially.

635
00:53:57,196 --> 00:54:01,241
THE QUEEN'S RESIDENCE
AT SANDRINGHAM

636
00:54:11,084 --> 00:54:13,003
That's a letter
of abdication...

637
00:54:13,086 --> 00:54:15,005
renouncing your claims
to the throne...

638
00:54:15,088 --> 00:54:18,050
and the claims
of your entire family.

639
00:54:18,133 --> 00:54:20,052
Sign it.

640
00:54:27,768 --> 00:54:29,770
Never.

641
00:54:40,447 --> 00:54:43,909
- Yes?

642
00:54:43,992 --> 00:54:46,954
Prime Minister, sorry to call so late,
but I'm afraid the queen is abdicating.

643
00:54:47,037 --> 00:54:48,664
What?

644
00:54:48,747 --> 00:54:52,960
Abdicated?
But that's not possible.

645
00:54:53,043 --> 00:54:55,170
I only wish that were true.

646
00:54:55,254 --> 00:54:59,216
- Let me talk to her. Maybe she just...
- Pascal, she's gone.

647
00:54:59,299 --> 00:55:01,927
My people have spent
the last 10 hours...

648
00:55:02,010 --> 00:55:05,472
trying to track down
the rightful heir to the throne...

649
00:55:05,556 --> 00:55:08,642
and they've come up with a name,
which they've double-checked.

650
00:55:08,725 --> 00:55:11,145
Who is it?

651
00:55:11,228 --> 00:55:14,231
- It's you.
- No!

652
00:55:18,402 --> 00:55:21,321
In the wake
of the return of the Crown Jewels...

653
00:55:21,405 --> 00:55:23,365
to a police station
in North London,

654
00:55:23,448 --> 00:55:26,118
Pascal Sauvage has requested
that his coronation...

655
00:55:26,160 --> 00:55:28,620
take place
this Thursday.

656
00:55:28,704 --> 00:55:32,499
In the House, the prime minister said he
was looking forward to the ceremony...

657
00:55:32,583 --> 00:55:35,002
and he believed that Monsieur Sauvage
will make a fine king...

658
00:55:35,085 --> 00:55:39,715
and will bring all that is
best about modern Europe
to our ancient institutions.

659
00:55:46,930 --> 00:55:49,516
Get your car keys.
We've got work to do.

660
00:55:49,600 --> 00:55:52,603
- Miss Campbell.
- Sauvage is heading back to France.

661
00:55:52,686 --> 00:55:57,191
He's invited 13 of
the richest criminal masterminds
in the world to meet him there.

662
00:55:57,274 --> 00:56:00,569
I'm sorry, Miss Campbell.
I'm off the case.

663
00:56:00,861 --> 00:56:02,196
It's been reassigned.

664
00:56:02,279 --> 00:56:04,823
I know.
Reassigned to me.

665
00:56:08,327 --> 00:56:10,913
- I want you with me.
- Just leave me alone.

666
00:56:11,038 --> 00:56:14,666
Are you gonna sit here in this
grotty flat feeling sorry for yourself?

667
00:56:14,750 --> 00:56:17,836
Or are you gonna get out there
and save your country?

668
00:56:19,004 --> 00:56:21,256
I'm gonna sit in the flat.

669
00:56:21,340 --> 00:56:25,260
- Johnny, this is ridiculous.
- I'm a spent force.

670
00:56:26,929 --> 00:56:29,640
Spent, my ass.

671
00:56:34,353 --> 00:56:36,104
Ow.

672
00:56:37,314 --> 00:56:39,691
Will... you...
please... stop?

673
00:56:52,079 --> 00:56:54,081
I'll just be a minute.

674
00:57:12,391 --> 00:57:15,477
NORTHERN FRANCE

675
00:57:37,457 --> 00:57:40,961
It'll be nightfall in an hour.
Then we can strike out for the chateau.

676
00:57:41,044 --> 00:57:44,173
The fact is, the moment Sauvage
gets that crown on his head,

677
00:57:44,256 --> 00:57:47,384
he'll be able to do whatever he likes
with the country that I love,

678
00:57:47,467 --> 00:57:50,095
and that is why you and I
have got to stop him.

679
00:57:51,805 --> 00:57:55,350
- Relishing the thought?
- Something like that.

680
00:57:58,187 --> 00:58:01,773
I suppose you've made love
to lots of women, haven't you, Johnny?

681
00:58:03,442 --> 00:58:08,030
Uh...
Uh, well, you know,

682
00:58:08,113 --> 00:58:10,699
one does one's best.

683
00:58:12,117 --> 00:58:13,869
It's just...

684
00:58:13,952 --> 00:58:18,790
Well, it's been three years
since my fiancé left me,

685
00:58:18,874 --> 00:58:22,544
and since then I haven't
made love to anyone.

686
00:58:22,628 --> 00:58:24,463
But then I met you...

687
00:58:25,714 --> 00:58:28,592
and I felt this...
hunger...

688
00:58:28,675 --> 00:58:31,762
deep down inside.

689
00:58:31,845 --> 00:58:34,932
I wanted to say things to you,
I wanted to do things to you...

690
00:58:35,015 --> 00:58:39,394
that I haven't wanted to do
in a very, very, very long time.

691
00:58:43,232 --> 00:58:45,984
What, uh...

692
00:58:46,068 --> 00:58:48,821
What sort of things
are we talking about?

693
00:58:48,904 --> 00:58:51,698
Things like
punching you in the face,

694
00:58:51,782 --> 00:58:54,993
kicking you in the backside for being
such a pompous, know-nothing asshole.

695
00:58:55,118 --> 00:58:59,206
But then I started to see beyond
the idiot that everybody else saw.

696
00:58:59,289 --> 00:59:02,209
I started to see
the man on the inside...

697
00:59:02,292 --> 00:59:06,255
who was determined to do his duty,
no matter what or who lay in his way.

698
00:59:06,338 --> 00:59:10,133
And I began to feel
other things for him,

699
00:59:10,217 --> 00:59:14,847
to want to do
other things for him.

700
00:59:14,930 --> 00:59:17,307
Things...

701
00:59:17,391 --> 00:59:21,019
involving plastic toys
and soft cheese?

702
00:59:21,103 --> 00:59:25,607
- What?
- What? What?

703
00:59:25,691 --> 00:59:29,987
You're toying with me.
You're telling me to stop in
the gentlest way you know how.

704
00:59:30,070 --> 00:59:32,030
No. N-N-No...

705
00:59:32,156 --> 00:59:33,740
You're such a special person...

706
00:59:33,824 --> 00:59:36,910
not to take advantage of me
while I'm vulnerable.

707
00:59:36,994 --> 00:59:39,413
- N-No... Well...
- So thank you...

708
00:59:39,496 --> 00:59:41,707
for being such a gentleman.

709
00:59:44,126 --> 00:59:46,336
Not at all.

710
01:00:06,982 --> 01:00:10,194
I know what you're thinking,
Miss Campbell.

711
01:00:10,319 --> 01:00:13,030
If we don't pull this off, God knows
what might happen to England.

712
01:00:13,113 --> 01:00:16,366
Actually, I was thinking there must be
a better way in than that pipe.

713
01:00:17,451 --> 01:00:19,495
Well, there isn't.

714
01:00:19,578 --> 01:00:22,498
I've analysed it from every angle,
